**Line 11-16:** The `/users` endpoint exposes user PII (names, emails) to **any unauthenticated caller**. This is a data exposure risk.

**Fix — add authentication middleware:**
```js
const authenticateToken = (req, res, next) => {
  const authHeader = req.headers['authorization'];
  const token = authHeader && authHeader.split(' ')[1];
  if (!token) return res.status(401).json({ error: 'Authentication required' });

  try {
    const user = jwt.verify(token, process.env.JWT_SECRET);
    req.user = user;
    next();
  } catch (err) {
    return res.status(403).json({ error: 'Invalid or expired token' });
  }
};

app.get('/users', authenticateToken, (req, res) => { /* ... */ });
```

### 3. No Rate Limiting (OWASP A04: Insecure Design)

Both endpoints are vulnerable to brute-force and denial-of-service attacks. There is no throttling of any kind.

**Fix — add `express-rate-limit`:**
```js
const rateLimit = require('express-rate-limit');

const limiter = rateLimit({
  windowMs: 15 * 60 * 1000, // 15 minutes
  max: 100,                   // 100 requests per window per IP
  standardHeaders: true,
  legacyHeaders: false,
  message: { error: 'Too many requests, please try again later.' },
});
app.use(limiter);
```

---

## 🟠 MEDIUM Severity

### 4. Sensitive Data Exposure (OWASP A02: Cryptographic Failures / A01: Broken Access Control)

**Lines 13-14:** Email addresses are returned in the `/users` response. Even when auth is added, responses should follow the principle of least privilege — only return fields the caller needs.

**Fix — strip sensitive fields or use a DTO:**
```js
app.get('/users', authenticateToken, (req, res) => {
  const safeUsers = users.map(({ id, name }) => ({ id, name }));
  res.json(safeUsers);
});
// Expose email only on GET /users/:id when the caller is authorized
```

### 5. No CORS Policy (OWASP A05: Security Misconfiguration)

Without explicit CORS configuration, the browser's same-origin policy applies — but this is fragile and won't protect API-only consumers. An explicit allowlist is critical.

**Fix:**
```js
const cors = require('cors');

app.use(cors({
  origin: ['https://yourdomain.com'],  // Explicit allowlist, never '*' in production
  methods: ['GET', 'POST'],
  allowedHeaders: ['Content-Type', 'Authorization'],
}));
```

### 6. No Global Error Handler (OWASP A05: Security Misconfiguration)

Express's default error handler sends **stack traces** in development mode. If `NODE_ENV` isn't set to `production`, attackers see internal paths, dependencies, and line numbers.

**Fix — add error-handling middleware at the end of the middleware chain:**
```js
// Must be defined AFTER all routes
app.use((err, req, res, next) => {
  console.error(err.stack);  // Log full error server-side
  res.status(err.status || 500).json({
    error: process.env.NODE_ENV === 'production'
      ? 'Internal server error'
      : err.message,           // Only show details in development
  });
});
```

### 7. No Request Size Limits (OWASP A04: Insecure Design)

When body parsing is eventually added, there are no size limits. A large payload could exhaust memory.

**Fix — set explicit limits:**
```js
app.use(express.json({ limit: '10kb' }));
app.use(express.urlencoded({ extended: false, limit: '10kb' }));
```

---

